statement.p:
If \mathbf u=(u_1,u_2) is a unit vector, then
\boxed{D_{\mathbf u}f(\mathbf p)=\nabla f(\mathbf p)\cdot\mathbf u.}
That is,
\boxed{D_{\mathbf u}f(a,b)=f_x(a,b)u_1+f_y(a,b)u_2.}

subsection.p:
The same formula holds in space:
\boxed{D_{\mathbf u}f(a,b,c)=\nabla f(a,b,c)\cdot\mathbf u,}
provided the first partial derivatives are continuous near the point.

Here is a function that shows what can go wrong:
f(x,y)=\begin{cases}\dfrac{x^2y}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0).\end{cases}
First compute the partial derivatives at the origin.

Now take the unit direction
\mathbf u=\left(\frac1{\sqrt2},\frac1{\sqrt2}\right).
Then
t\mathbf u=\left(\frac{t}{\sqrt2},\frac{t}{\sqrt2}\right).
For t\ne0,

  f\left(\frac{t}{\sqrt2},\frac{t}{\sqrt2}\right) \amp= \frac{\left(\frac{t}{\sqrt2}\right)^2\left(\frac{t}{\sqrt2}\right)}{\left(\frac{t}{\sqrt2}\right)^2+\left(\frac{t}{\sqrt2}\right)^2}
  \amp= \frac{\frac{t^3}{2\sqrt2}}{t^2}
  \amp= \frac{t}{2\sqrt2}.

Therefore

  D_{\mathbf u}f(0,0) \amp= \lim_{t\to0}\frac{f(t\mathbf u)-f(0,0)}{t}
  \amp= \lim_{t\to0}\frac{\frac{t}{2\sqrt2}}{t}
  \amp= \frac1{2\sqrt2}.

The directional derivative exists, but it is not 0. The gradient formula fails.

statement.p:
Suppose the gradient formula holds at a point \mathbf p, and suppose
\nabla f(\mathbf p)\ne\mathbf 0.
Among all unit directions \mathbf u,
\boxed{D_{\mathbf u}f(\mathbf p)}
is largest when
\boxed{\mathbf u=\frac{\nabla f(\mathbf p)}{\|\nabla f(\mathbf p)\|}.}
The largest value is
\boxed{\|\nabla f(\mathbf p)\|.}
It is smallest when
\boxed{\mathbf u=-\frac{\nabla f(\mathbf p)}{\|\nabla f(\mathbf p)\|}.}
The smallest value is
\boxed{-\|\nabla f(\mathbf p)\|.}

